    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Neighborhood pages</strong> are landing pages targeting specific neighborhoods, districts, suburbs, or zip codes within a larger metro area. They go deeper than city pages by capturing hyperlocal searches — while a city page targets "plumber in Austin," a neighborhood page targets "plumber in South Congress." Google's Local Finder increasingly favors hyperlocal content, and neighborhood pages fill the gap where broad city queries become too competitive to win.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Primary signal</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Geographic relevance</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Recommended range</div>
            <div class="tms-value">5-15 per city</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most businesses build a city page and stop there. Neighborhood pages are the next layer down — and they're where local competitors are typically thinnest. If you operate in a metro with 500,000+ residents, this is where your best untapped traffic lives.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are neighborhood pages?</h2>
        <p>Neighborhood pages are dedicated landing pages built around a specific district, neighborhood, suburb, or zip code within a larger metro area. They sit one level below city pages in a geographic content hierarchy and target search queries that include neighborhood names instead of city names.</p>
        <p>The distinction matters because search intent at the neighborhood level is fundamentally different. Someone searching "dentist in Houston" is early in discovery mode. Someone searching "dentist in Montrose" knows where they want to go — they just need to find who's there. Conversion rates on hyperlocal queries run significantly higher as a result.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>City page</strong> — targets "[service] in [city]" — broad intent, higher competition</li>
          <li><strong>Neighborhood page</strong> — targets "[service] in [neighborhood]" — narrow intent, lower competition, higher conversion</li>
          <li><strong>Service area page</strong> — covers a geographic radius without neighborhood-level specificity</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's stance on hyperlocal content</div>
          <p>Google's Local Finder results increasingly surface content that matches the specific geographic context of a query. Pages with genuine neighborhood-level content — landmarks, local customer stories, neighborhood-specific considerations — outperform generic templates in local pack rankings.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why neighborhood pages matter for local SEO</h2>
        <p>City pages compete against every local business, directory, and national chain in your market. Neighborhood pages carve out a lane most competitors haven't entered yet. There are four concrete reasons to build them:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Lower competition, higher intent.</strong> Queries like "electrician in Uptown" have a fraction of the competition of "electrician in Dallas," but the searcher is just as ready to call. Less competition plus equivalent intent equals faster rankings.</li>
          <li><strong>Proximity signal support.</strong> Google's local ranking algorithm weights proximity heavily. Neighborhood pages create geographic relevance signals that reinforce your proximity to that specific area — useful even for businesses without a physical location there.</li>
          <li><strong>Content depth that directories can't match.</strong> Yelp and Google Maps can't write a page about your experience working in Oak Cliff's historic homes. You can. Original hyperlocal content is a defensible moat.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive edge.</strong> Most competitors create city pages and stop. Businesses in metros above 500,000 population that build neighborhood pages dominate an overlooked hyperlocal layer of search that their competitors aren't contesting.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How neighborhood pages work</h2>
        <p>A neighborhood page works by combining genuine local content with standard on-page SEO. The key word is "genuine" — Google's quality algorithms are effective at detecting template pages where only the neighborhood name has been swapped.</p>

        <h3>Content requirements</h3>
        <p>Each page needs content that could only be written about that specific neighborhood. That includes:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Neighborhood character and demographics relevant to your service</li>
          <li>Local landmarks, streets, or institutions that orient the reader</li>
          <li>Service-specific considerations (e.g., older housing stock, building codes, parking restrictions)</li>
          <li>Customer testimonials or case studies from that neighborhood specifically</li>
          <li>Information a local would recognize as accurate</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Geographic content silo structure</h3>
        <p>Neighborhood pages work best when wired into a proper geographic hierarchy. The recommended structure:</p>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Geographic content silo</span><br>
          <span class="uf-new">Homepage</span><br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="uf-arrow">└→</span> <span class="uf-new">/city/austin/</span> <span class="uf-comment">(City page — "plumber in Austin")</span><br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="uf-arrow">└→</span> <span class="uf-new">/city/austin/south-congress/</span> <span class="uf-comment">(Neighborhood — "plumber in South Congress")</span><br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="uf-arrow">└→</span> <span class="uf-new">/city/austin/east-austin/</span> <span class="uf-comment">(Neighborhood — "plumber in East Austin")</span>
        </div>
        <p>Link neighborhood pages up to the parent city page, and link city pages down to their neighborhood children. This creates topical authority and distributes link equity efficiently across the cluster.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Neighborhood page types — which format to use</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Best for</th><th>Content depth</th><th>SEO strength</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Full neighborhood guide</strong></td>
                <td>Primary service areas</td>
                <td>800-1,500 words</td>
                <td>Strongest</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Service + location hybrid</strong></td>
                <td>Secondary neighborhoods</td>
                <td>400-800 words</td>
                <td>Strong</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Zip code page</strong></td>
                <td>Service area businesses</td>
                <td>300-600 words</td>
                <td>Moderate</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Template-only page</strong></td>
                <td>Avoid</td>
                <td>Thin</td>
                <td>Doorway page risk</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real neighborhood page examples</h2>
        <p>Two concrete examples of how businesses build neighborhood pages that rank and convert.</p>

        <h3>1. Roofing company in Dallas</h3>
        <p>A roofing company creates neighborhood pages for Uptown, Deep Ellum, Oak Cliff, and Bishop Arts. The Oak Cliff page discusses the neighborhood's historic homes from the 1920s-1950s and the specific roofing considerations — restoration versus replacement, period-appropriate materials, and how Dallas's hail patterns affect older wood shingles differently than modern composites. A contractor in a generic city page couldn't write that. The Oak Cliff page can.</p>

        <h3>2. Real estate agent in a major metro</h3>
        <p>An agent builds neighborhood pages for 10 districts, each including average home prices for the last 12 months, school ratings, walkability scores, and a "living in [neighborhood]" guide covering commute times, local restaurants, and housing stock type. Supporting blog content — "Best Restaurants in Montrose" — links to the Montrose neighborhood page. The internal linking structure builds hyperlocal authority that competitor agents, who only have a single city page, can't replicate.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Neighborhood pages vs city pages — when to use each</h2>
        <p>Both belong in a local SEO strategy. The question is which level to prioritize first.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Build neighborhood pages when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You operate in a metro with 500,000+ population</li>
              <li>You can write genuinely unique content per neighborhood</li>
              <li>Your city page already ranks on page 1 or 2</li>
              <li>Competitors haven't built hyperlocal pages yet</li>
              <li>You serve specific districts with distinct characteristics</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Stick to city pages when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You're in a smaller market (under 100,000 population)</li>
              <li>You don't have neighborhood-specific knowledge to write authentically</li>
              <li>City page rankings haven't been established yet</li>
              <li>You'd have to use thin templates to scale</li>
              <li>You serve a wide regional area, not distinct neighborhoods</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for neighborhood pages</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Write unique content per page.</strong> The neighborhood name swap is not a content strategy. Write at least one fact, story, or consideration that is specific to that neighborhood and couldn't appear on any other page.</li>
          <li><strong>Target 5-15 neighborhoods per city.</strong> Start with your highest-volume service areas. More pages with thin content hurts more than fewer pages with depth.</li>
          <li><strong>Wire the geographic hierarchy correctly.</strong> Link neighborhood pages to parent city pages and back. Google follows this structure to understand topical and geographic relationships.</li>
          <li><strong>Include local landmarks and context.</strong> Mention streets, parks, institutions, or local events that a resident would recognize. This is the local relevance signal that generic content can't manufacture.</li>
          <li><strong>Add neighborhood-specific social proof.</strong> A testimonial from a customer in that neighborhood, or a case study of a job done there, provides credibility signals that AI-generated content cannot replicate.</li>
          <li><strong>Support with blog content.</strong> Publish supporting articles — neighborhood guides, area comparisons, local tips — and link them to the neighborhood page. This builds topical authority faster than the landing page alone.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Doorway page risk — the 50-thin-pages trap</div>
          <p>Creating hundreds of neighborhood pages with template-only content — same copy, just the neighborhood name swapped — puts you in doorway page territory. Google's quality guidelines explicitly target these. When caught, rankings drop sitewide, not just on the thin pages. Five strong neighborhood pages outperform 50 thin ones every time.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common neighborhood page mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Template content with swapped names</strong> — Google's quality systems detect this pattern and classify pages as doorways</li>
          <li><strong>No internal linking to city page</strong> — orphaned neighborhood pages lose the authority transfer from the parent hierarchy</li>
          <li><strong>Targeting non-existent neighborhoods</strong> — making up district names that locals don't use sends a relevance mismatch signal</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring mobile and map pack optimization</strong> — most hyperlocal searches happen on mobile; neighborhood pages without schema and a Google Business Profile citation underperform</li>
          <li><strong>Creating pages before rankings exist</strong> — build your city page first, establish some authority, then expand to neighborhoods</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How many neighborhood pages should I create?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Only as many as you can fill with genuinely unique content. Most businesses benefit from 5-15 neighborhood pages in their primary city. Create pages for neighborhoods where you have customers, local knowledge, and enough unique information to differentiate each page from the others.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Do neighborhood pages cannibalize city pages?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Not if structured properly. City pages target broader "[service] in [city]" queries while neighborhood pages target narrower "[service] in [neighborhood]" queries. Linking them in a parent-child hierarchy helps Google understand the relationship, so they complement rather than compete with each other.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can service area businesses use neighborhood pages?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Service area businesses benefit heavily since they lack a storefront pin for each area. Neighborhood content creates geographic relevance signals that a Google Business Profile listing cannot provide for distant neighborhoods. A plumber without an office in South Congress can still rank for "plumber in South Congress" with a strong neighborhood page.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What makes a neighborhood page different from a city page?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>City pages target broad metro-level queries with wide geographic relevance. Neighborhood pages go deeper — they capture hyperlocal intent with district-specific content: local landmarks, neighborhood history, specific customer testimonials, and service considerations unique to that area's housing stock or demographics.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">When do neighborhood pages become doorway pages?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>When they use thin, template-only content with just the neighborhood name swapped in. Google's quality guidelines classify these as doorway pages. Each neighborhood page must contain genuinely unique content. Five strong pages outperform 50 thin ones — and thin pages risk a sitewide quality penalty.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

